OpenWrt @VERSION@ USB overlay/swap install package for @MODEL@

Purpose:
  Install OpenWrt by bootloader TFTP recovery, prepare a USB drive for overlay
  and swap, then verify that the router booted with USB overlay and USB swap.

Contents:
  firmware/@FIRMWARE_IMAGE@
  firmware/SHA256SUMS
  install.sh
  scripts/upload_firmware_tftp.sh
  scripts/prepare_usb_overlay_swap.sh
  scripts/verify_router_overlay_swap.sh

Firmware profile:
  This image includes light LuCI web administration, web attended sysupgrade
  support, USB storage, ext4, block-mount and USB swap support. It intentionally
  does not include the LuCI package manager. The firmware contains the default
  USB overlay/swap boot policy for labels overlay and swap.

Default USB layout:
  partition 1: 512 MiB ext4, label overlay, router overlay
  partition 2: 128 MiB swap, label swap, router swap
  partition 3: remaining space ext4, label data, user data

Requirements:
  - Linux host connected by Ethernet to a router LAN port.
  - Host wired Ethernet configured with static IPv4 192.168.1.2/24 for
    bootloader TFTP recovery.
  - USB flash drive visible as a whole /dev/sdX disk on the host.
  - Prepared USB flash inserted before booting the flashed firmware.
  - SSH access to the freshly booted router. The default target is
    root@192.168.1.1 and can be changed with --router.

List required host commands:
  ./install.sh --get-deps

Recommended one-command install:
  ./install.sh --usb /dev/sdX

All install.sh options:
  --get-deps                  list required host commands
  --firmware FILE             firmware image to upload by TFTP
  --usb /dev/sdX              host USB disk to format
  --tftp-host 192.168.1.1     bootloader TFTP host
  --tftp-client-ip CIDR       host IPv4 CIDR for TFTP recovery
  --overlay-mib N             overlay partition size, default 512
  --swap-mib N                swap partition size, default 128
  --router root@192.168.1.1   router SSH target
  --url http://192.168.1.1    router web URL opened at the end when possible

The one-command helper runs these scripts in order:
  1. scripts/upload_firmware_tftp.sh
     Requires and verifies firmware/SHA256SUMS, then uploads firmware by TFTP.
     The script waits until the configured host IPv4 is present. It does not
     change host network settings.
     If no firmware file is provided, it uses the single entry listed in
     firmware/SHA256SUMS and stops on zero, multiple or missing entries.

  2. scripts/prepare_usb_overlay_swap.sh
     Partitions and formats the USB drive on the host.

  3. scripts/verify_router_overlay_swap.sh
     Verifies that the firmware boot policy mounted USB overlay and enabled
     USB swap.

The prepared USB flash must be inserted before the router boots the flashed
firmware. Delayed insertion is not part of the normal install flow.

Run the scripts manually only if you need to repeat or debug one step.

Expected router result:
  /dev/sda1 mounted at /overlay
  overlayfs:/overlay mounted at /
  /dev/sda2 active in /proc/swaps
  LuCI reachable at the configured router web URL

Upgrade note:
  This image is intended to be maintainable through image-based upgrades.
  Use the web attended sysupgrade page or SSH-based tools for upgrades.
  Avoid using the LuCI package manager on this hardware; it is memory-heavy
  for a 32 MiB RAM router.

Safety:
  - Do not run install.sh with sudo or as root. Helper scripts ask for sudo
    only when they need to write the USB disk layout.
  - The scripts do not change host network settings.
  - Replace /dev/sdX with the whole USB disk, not a partition.
  - The USB preparation step destroys all existing data on that USB disk.
  - USB formatting starts only after you type FORMAT at the prompt.
  - Do not disconnect power while the router is flashing.
  - Old routers can need several minutes during flashing, first boot and reboot.
  - Do not unplug the USB flash from a running router after USB overlay or swap
    is active.
